ThinkPart(
    type='think',
    think="Great! So the API service has access to `AssetsClient` through the cl
ient package. But looking at the existing usecases in `internal/biz/wapi/`, they
typically define a smaller interface for the assets client to make testing easie
r.\n\nFor example, `fish.go` probably has:\n```go\ntype fishAssetsClient interfa
ce {\n    LoadAssetOne(ctx context.Context, uid, propId int64) (int64, error)\n 
  // ...\n}\n```\n\nBut for the quest system, I only need `GainAll` to give mult
iple assets at once. So I'll define:\n```go\ntype questAssetsClient interface {\
n    GainAll(ctx context.Context, uid int64, gains map[int64]int64) error\n}\n``
`\n\nAnd in the usecase constructor, I'll accept `*client.AssetsClient` or the i
nterface.\n\nWait, looking at how Wire works, if I define the interface in the b
iz layer and have Wire bind it, I need to add a wire.Bind. But looking at the le
aderboard usecase, it doesn't use the assets client at all - it only uses `asset
sBasicRepo` for reading level/exp.\n\nFor the quest usecase, I have two options:
\n1. Use `assetsClient.GainAll()` for direct asset rewards\n2. Send all rewards 
via mail (simpler, no need for assets client)\n\nThe PRD says asset rewards shou
ld be direct, but mail is acceptable for道具. Since this is a new feature and to
keep things simpler, I could send all rewards via mail. But the PRD is pretty sp
ecific about direct asset gains.\n\nActually, looking at the leaderboard code, i
t sends all rewards via `systemMailRepo`. If that's acceptable for leaderboard, 
it might be acceptable for quests too. But the PRD explicitly differentiates.\n\
nLet me check if there's any existing usecase that uses the assets client.",
    encrypted=None
)
